{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 11:04:26.293642", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network snapshot and findings\\n\\nSummary\\n- Control-plane (OSPF) and inter-router IP routing appear converged and healthy: core, distribution and server-access routers all have the expected OSPF-learned routes for the 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 subnets and the server farm 10.200.0.0/24.\\n- Server-side infrastructure (server_access_router, dhcp_server, dns_server, web_server_0, load_balancer) is up and reachable at the router level; DHCP server process is running and actively issuing leases.\\n- Anomalous behaviour is observed at the host (edge) level: sampled hosts do not have IP addresses / default routes configured even though the DHCP server shows active leases for those MACs. This results in “Network is unreachable” from the host when trying to reach server IPs (e.g., DNS).\\n\\nKey evidence (raw observations)\\n- OSPF / routing convergence (examples from routers):\\n  - router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, router_dist_* outputs contain OSPF routes for the 10.1.x.0/24 and 10.2.x.0/24 networks and the inter-router point-to-point links — consistent, recent route ages, no obvious OSPF adjacency flaps in the snapshots.\\n  - server_access_router shows 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected (br0).\\n- Server and DHCP:\\n  - server_access_router -> dhcp_server ping: 4/4 replies, low RTT (0.38–1.37 ms) — server farm reachable from router.\\n  - isc-dhcp-server status: active (running).\\n  - /var/lib/dhcp/dhcpd.leases contains many active leases. Example: host_1_1_1_1 has an active lease entry:\\n    - lease 10.1.1.13 { hardware ethernet 46:2d:eb:8e:00:21; client-hostname \"host_1_1_1_1\"; binding state active; ... }\\n  - DHCP leases for many hosts (including host_2_1_1_1) are present and recent.\\n- Host-side (sampled hosts):\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip addr: eth0 appears UP but no inet address listed; no IP route shown.\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip addr: same — interface UP but no inet configured.\\n  - From host_1_1_1_1: ping to dns_server failed immediately: \"ping: connect: Network is unreachable\" — indicates host lacks IP address / default route.\\n- Reachability tool output:\\n  - A bulk reachability run shows many host-to-host pings succeeding (many 0% loss), but several server-to-host pings and some server-origin pings are labeled \"unknown\" (not attempted or device not running). Some individual host-to-server pings from sampled hosts show they cannot reach servers (see host-origin ping failure above).\\n\\nAnomalies detected\\n1. Host(s) lacking configured IP addresses despite leases on DHCP server\\n   - DHCP server has active lease entries for the sampled host MACs (e.g., host_1_1_1_1 → 10.1.1.13), but the host\\'s local network stack shows eth0 without an assigned IPv4 address and no IP routing.\\n   - Result: host cannot reach server farm (DNS/web) — tool observed \"Network is unreachable\" from the host.\\n\\n2. Inconsistent reachability / tool reporting for server-origin pings\\n   - Several server-origin pings in the reachability output are marked \"unknown\" (no result). That is likely due to the reachability probe not executing from those endpoints or those endpoint processes not running in the lab at probe time — not necessarily a forwarding/routing problem. Router-level pings to servers are fine.\\n\\nLocalization — where the fault is\\n- The problem is localized at the host-edge (host OS or the immediate host connectivity) rather than core routing or DHCP relay:\\n  - DHCP server and server-access router are reachable from the network and actively exchanging traffic.\\n  - OSPF routing is present and distributed across cores/distribution routers — routers have routes to the host subnets.\\n  - The DHCP server has recorded leases for the affected hosts’ MAC addresses, so DHCP requests reached the server and were processed.\\n  - However, the host (sampled) network stack shows no configured IP — the failure point is where the lease is supposed to be applied (host-side) or the host is not binding/using the lease.\\n\\nMost likely root-cause(s)\\n- Host-side DHCP client / configuration issue (primary candidate)\\n  - The DHCP server granted leases (evidence: dhcpd.leases). The hosts’ NICs are up but show no inet address. This strongly suggests the DHCP client on the host either:\\n    - is not running or failed to start,\\n    - did not accept/apply the lease, or\\n    - is misconfigured (wrong DHCP client implementation, static config preventing DHCP, or misapplied network namespace).\\n- Alternative host-side causes (less likely but possible)\\n  - Host processes are running in a different network namespace than the interface we inspected, causing the management view to show no address while the host namespace actually has one.\\n  - A timing race where the dhclient had a lease but host abandoned it (but lease presence plus lack of address on host suggests not applied).\\n- Not likely the network/DHCP-relay/routing layers:\\n  - DHCP server is reachable from server_access_router and is issuing leases; routers have OSPF routes for host subnets; server_access_router pings to DHCP server succeed. This makes an infrastructure-level DHCP distribution or OSPF routing problem improbable for these symptoms.\\n\\nAdditional notes / suggested follow-up checks (diagnostic steps, not mitigations)\\n- On an affected host (e.g., host_1_1_1_1):\\n  - Check DHCP client status/logs (e.g., ps for dhclient / system logs) to confirm whether a DHCP client is running and whether it requested/received its lease.\\n  - Inspect kernel/network namespaces to confirm the interface and address list are in the expected namespace (ip netns or similar).\\n  - Run tcpdump on the host interface while initiating DHCP client to verify DHCP DISCOVER/OFFER/REQUEST/ACK exchange and whether the host receives the DHCP ACK.\\n- On the access switch / port:\\n  - Verify link/port status and that the MAC observed by the DHCP server matches the host\\'s NIC MAC on the switch port (the lease record matches the host MAC, so likely OK).\\n- On DHCP server:\\n  - Confirm that DHCP ACKs are being sent and there are no errors applying the lease (logs already show leases created).\\n- If desired, sample more hosts to determine whether the issue is isolated to a few hosts or widespread across edge hosts.\\n\\nBottom line\\n- Network control and server-side infrastructure are healthy (routers OSPF, server_access_router, DHCP server, DNS, web servers appear reachable from routers).\\n- The active anomaly is at the host edge: hosts have DHCP leases recorded on the DHCP server but the hosts themselves lack configured IP addresses and therefore cannot reach servers. The most probable root cause is a host-side DHCP client or host network configuration problem (hosts failing to apply leases), not a core routing or DHCP relay failure., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='85a50dea-0d47-4bc4-a17a-48f35e325505'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
